  "title": "Web Bluetooth",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "3966d9eed92475c7",
      "text": "Chrome 53 has an Origin Trial for Bluetooth, which means that websites can opt-in to use this feature and automatically enable Web Bluetooth for all their visitors. It is the first time such technology enabling IoT directly from the web is deployed in the wild. [https://medium.com/@urish/is-now-a-good-time-to-start-using-web-bluetooth-hint-yes-yes-it-is-99e998d7b9f6#.u9l7mnyww post]"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "a411c484d03b70d9",
      "text": "BLE has two roles: Central and Peripheral. The Central scans for Peripherals and can be connected to several Peripherals at once, depending on the hardware. Peripherals are passive — which means they can’t initiate the connection, and they can usually only be connected with one peer (i.e., one Central). "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "c7ecfb48d92fc5d9",
      "text": "Most hardware supports both roles — that is, both Central and Peripheral — but not always. For example, my Nexus 5 phone can only be a Central, but not a peripheral. With the newer Nexus 5X, both modes are supported. But it’s important to note that there are no Central-to-Central or Peripheral-to-Peripheral connections; it is always Central-to-Peripheral.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "0c55b507b5b9fd3c",
      "text": "Web Bluetooth only supports the Central role, which means you can only connect with Peripherals. This means you can’t establish a direct BLE connection between two web pages on different devices using Web Bluetooth. You could, however, make a connection between Web Bluetooth (as a Central) and a native app implementing a Peripheral service.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "48104ea261dfab4f",
      "text": "Finally, in Web Bluetooth’s current state, you can’t scan for all devices around you — for good privacy reasons — and you can’t just connect to any device any time. So certain use cases, such polling a device periodically in the background, controlling a device through push notification received via Web Push API, or putting on a show for your website visitors by making their smart lights at home go all crazy, aren’t really possible just yet.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "775d9d6a4032abd5",
      "text": "it it seems like a spec is being drafted to add scanning capabilities to Web Bluetooth, so we’ll just have to wait and see what the future holds!"
    }
